<br>
It is possible to kite them completely over the water, and duck yer head under to snare/AE.  If you have lev up to get back above water for the running part, it makes raptors very safe as it's incredibly easy to get away.  And once you get used to it, kiting in the water isn't all that bad.  Make a stop in Oasis on the way there and kite a croc in the ocean for a safe way to learn to kite in the water if you want.<br>
<br>
However, after doing this my first couple kites, I found the delays involved in stopping movement underwater to cast to be somewhat annoying, and so I would snare underwater, and then go back to land for the actual nuking part (once snared, the beach is plenty large).  A few more kites like this, and I moved back to what seems to be the standard - group them over water, then snare and nuke on land.  Using the water is a great learning tool, but you can kite faster on land.<br>
<br>
Also, I don't understand why everyone says that you will take hits quadding these.  I pull using only aggro from being near them, running along over the water out past the beach, running circles over the water, and then running a straight line over the beach (starting from a ways out over water) to get distance and snare.  I usually get to distance about mid-way across the south beech of the small island (where I like to kite the best, though I've found kiting along the south edge of large is easy too).  I've been there for 1/2 of 54 now, and haven't taken a single hit yet (though one did try and hit me, but missed) - if I hadn't asked a friend that was also soloing them with me, I wouldn't even know how much damage they hit for.  So, I am the only person I know of that quad's them completly buffless (except jboots and lev), no skin, no shielding, don't even invis to med up (medding on large usually, or on small under the iksar guy).  Then again, maybe I'm just insane.<br>
<br>
